Kasus Ebola pertama di Amerika Serikat
Kasus virus mematikan Ebola terjadi untuk pertama kalinya di Amerika Serikat.
Kasus virus mematikan Ebola terjadi untuk pertama kalinya di Amerika Serikat.
Virus itu dilaporkan menjangkiti seorang pasien yang tidak disebutkan identitasnya di Dallas, Negara Bagian Texas. Kini, pasien itu tengah menjalani isolasi di Rumah Sakit Texas Health Presbyterian.
Pasien tersebut diduga telah terjangkit virus Ebola di Liberia sebelum hijrah ke AS dua pekan yang lalu.
"Pasien yang melakukan perjalanan dari Liberia ini terdiagnosa Ebola ketika tiba di AS," kata Direktur Pusat Pengendalian Penyakit dan Pencegahan, Thomas Frieden.
Menurut Frieden, pasien itu meninggalkan Liberia pada 19 September dan tiba di AS pada hari berikutnya untuk mengunjungi kerabat.
Gejala Ebola terlihat pada pasien pada 24 September. Dia dimasukkan ke dalam ruang isolasi empat hari kemudian.
Pejabat rumah sakit mengatakan kepada para wartawan bahwa mereka mempunyai sejumlah prosedur untuk menangani setiap penyakit tertentu.
Kasus di Kota Dallas merupakan kasus virus Ebola pertama yang didiagnosa di AS. Sebelumnya, terdapat tiga relawan medis asal AS yang terlebih dulu diketahui mengidap Ebola di Afrika sebelum akhirnya dibawa ke AS untuk menjalani pengobatan.
Informasi awal menunjukkan pasien yang tidak disebutkan namanya itu tidak terlibat dalam kegiatan merawat pasien-pasien yang terinfeksi Ebola saat berada di Liberia.
Meski demikian, para petugas medis kini mengidentifikasi semua orang yang telah berhubungan dengan pasien yang telah terinfeksi virus tersebut.
Mereka akan diawasi selama 21 hari untuk melihat apakah mereka menampakkan gejala-gejala virus Ebola.
Menurut Frieden, anggota keluarga yang berhubungan langsung dengan pasien kemungkinan bisa terjangkit Ebola dalam beberapa minggu mendatang.
"Intinya saya percaya kita bisa mengendalikan kasus Ebola ini sehingga tidak menyebar luas di negara ini. Kita akan hentikan penyebaran virus itu di sini."
Organisasi Kesehatan Dunia (WHO) mengatakan sejauh ini sudah lebih dari 3.000 orang meninggal karena virus Ebola yang terjadi di sebagian besar kawasan Afrika Barat.
</doc>
<doc id='bbc_091117_guerilla' type='mono' source_url='http://www.bbc.co.uk/indonesia/bahasa_inggris/2009/11/091117_guerilla' term='ebola'>
Guerilla atau Gorilla
One sort of confusing words are homophones – that means two words which sound the same but have different meanings.
One sort of confusing words are homophones – that means two words which sound the same but have different meanings.
Here’s a basic example: two – the number two (TWO) and too, meaning ‘as well’ (TOO).
Another sort of words are homographs – that means two words which are spelt the same but have different meanings.
Here’s an example:  tear, meaning to rip, and tear, meaning water in your eye, which are both spelt TEAR.
Now, let’s join Finn and Abigail, who are going to look at one pair of confusing homophones.
Finn:                    Hello and welcome to Soundalikes, the quick guide to words in the news which can be easily confused because they sound the same but have different meanings.   So, which words are we looking at today, Abigail?
Abigail: Yes, today I’ve got two words, very different meanings - 'gorilla' and 'guerilla'.  Sounds like one word, but it’s two.
Finn:                    Ok – 'gorilla' and 'guerilla', right.  They sound pretty much exactly the same and perhaps one of them is a hairy animal? We’ll soon find out.  Let's hear these words in context.
"Police say the suspects attended guerrilla-style training camps, and that weapons and ammunition were seized in the raids."
"Africa’s Western Gorilla has this year moved into the critically endangered category, decimated by trade in bush meat and the ebola virus"
Finn:                    Right, so in the first one we heard about guerrilla-style training camps, and the second one was talking about an African Western gorilla – which was endangered.  Abigail – can you enlighten us on the difference please?
Abigail:               Yes – ok well the first one is guerrilla, which I think is probably a Spanish word originally, and it’s spelled GUERRILLA – which we say in English – Guerrilla.  And it’s a fighter in an unofficial military group maybe trying to bring down the government. So that’s one kind of Guerrilla.
Finn:                    Ah, that’s our first Guerrilla and the clue to the meaning  as always is in the context?
Abigail:               Yes, exactly.  So in that first report you played you heard words like weapon and ammunition, you had police raids – so that tells you that you’re talking about some kind of fighters, in this case guerrillas.
Finn:                    Ok – and the second gorilla, now that was a rather different kind of gorilla it’s fair to say.
Abigail:               Yes exactly – the second gorilla was gorilla as in large ape –
GORILLA  and gorillas live as we heard in Western Africa.
Finn: Indeed, so that was gorilla – the hairy one and guerrilla the armed one.
Abigail:               Possibly also hairy.
Finn:                    Could be.  Two more confusing words from Soundalikes.
"Police say the suspects attended guerrilla-style training camps, and that weapons and ammunition were seized in the raids."
"Africa’s Western Gorilla has this year moved into the critically endangered category, decimated by trade in bush meat and the ebola virus"
So we heard Finn and Abigail talking about the words guerrilla and gorilla. Let’s see if you can identify the two different words when used in a sentence.
So, the two meanings are: Guerilla – a type of fighter, and gorilla – a large animal?
Let’s recap the spellings of those two words. Guerrilla – a fighter is spelt GUERILLA and gorilla – an animal is GORILLA.
</doc>
